#Plots
sparr.birds <- data.frame(as.numeric(rownames(sparrows)),sparrows[,1:6])

labs.diagonal <- c("Total length","Alar extent","L. beak & head","L. humerous","L. keel & sternum")

scatterplotMatrix(~Total_length+Alar_extent+L_beak_head+L_humerous+L_keel_sternum | Survivorship, data=sparr.birds, var.labels=labs.diagonal,cex.labels=0.7, diagonal="boxplot",pch=c(1,16),col=rep("black",2))
## Warning in applyDefaults(diagonal, defaults = list(method = "adaptiveDensity"),
## : unnamed diag arguments, will be ignored

library(car)
# Visualize boxplot - in general 
boxplot(sparrows[,3:6])

# ggplot
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=L_humerous, y=Survivorship)) + geom_boxplot()

# In L_humerous, NS has a much wider range which compares to the S. 
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=L_keel_sternum, y=Alar_extent, fill=Survivorship, color=Survivorship)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method=lm)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# the trend (slopes) of regression / ranges between  Alar_extent and L_keel_sternum, in NS and S, are significantly different.
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=L_humerous, y=Survivorship)) + geom_violin()

# the distribustion shapes of L_humerous are different between NS and S.
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Total_length, fill=Survivorship, color=Survivorship)) + geom_density(alpha=0.3, aes(y=..scaled..)) 
## Warning: The dot-dot notation (`..scaled..`) was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `after_stat(scaled)` instead.

#the distribution shapes of Total_length are different between NS and S.
